alcium ions","Magnesium ions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring cerebral ischaemia, energy failure leads to membrane depolarisation and excessive glutamate release. When glutamate binds to its receptors, particularly N-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptors, it triggers a massive influx of \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcium ions\u003C/strong\u003E into neurons. This calcium overload initiates various destructive cellular processes leading to cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium ions\u003C/strong\u003E do increase during ischaemia through various channels, but this is not the primary ionic derangement leading to cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPotassium ions\u003C/strong\u003E actually leak out of cells during ischaemia as the sodium-potassium ATPase fails due to energy depletion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChloride ions\u003C/strong\u003E play a minor role in the pathophysiology of cerebral ischaemia compared to the dramatic calcium influx.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMagnesium ions\u003C/strong\u003E typically decrease during ischaemia as they are displaced from NMDA receptors by calcium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this calcium-mediated excitotoxicity cascade has led to various therapeutic strategies in stroke management, though many calcium channel blockers have proved disappointing in clinical trials. The focus has shifted to early reperfusion strategies to prevent this destructive cascade from being initiated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glutamate receptor overstimulation leads to excessive calcium influx into neurons during cerebral ischaemia.","Calcium overload triggers multiple pathways leading to neuronal cell death in stroke.","This excitotoxicity cascade is a key therapeutic target in acute stroke management."],"references":["Singh V, Mishra VN, Chaurasia RN, Joshi D, Pandey V. Modes of Calcium Regulation in Ischemic Neuron. Indian J Clin Biochem. 2019 Jul;34(3):246-253. doi: 10.1007/s12291-019-00838-9. Epub 2019 Jun 20. PMID: 31391713; PMCID: PMC6660593.","Lee RHC, Lee MHH, Wu CYC, Couto E Silva A, Possoit HE, Hsieh TH, Minagar A, Lin HW. Cerebral ischemia and neuroregeneration. Neural Regen Res. 2018 Mar;13(3):373-385. doi: 10.4103/1673-5374.228711. Erratum in: Neural Regen Res. 2022 Aug;17(8):1639. doi: 10.4103/1673-5374.332994. PMID: 29623912; PMCID: PMC5900490.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60680"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60680","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60680"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T09:05:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T14:03:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9151"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75172"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"32","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/32"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurosurgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"